            <i class="fa fa-bar-chart-o fa-fw"></i> UNDERSTANDING CRIME DATA
          </div>
          <div class="panel-body">
<p>A better understanding of an area’s crime patterns can lead to safer, more informed decision-making for residents and visitors.
</p>

<p>Los Angeles and its surrounding counties are inhabited by international students, small-town Americans, and tourists from all over the world. Many of them need to make location-based decisions every day, like choosing where to live or rent, which route to take to work, or even which grocery store to shop in. But in a city where diversity is an active character, and each neighborhood has its own personality, knowing the relative safety of a neighborhood and understanding an area’s crime will facilitate better decision-making.
</p>
<p>
To provide transparency and a better understanding of safe locations, Los Angeles and its surrounding areas make crime data available to the public. The statistics reflect crimes that are reported to law enforcement agencies. However, people cannot completely rely on crime data to make accurate judgments about the safety of  an area. Crime data can only be based on crimes that are reported to police, and the likelihood of people reporting crimes has nuanced, confounding variables that are unique to each neighborhood.
</p>
<p>            
It is important to note that crime data is transcribed from original reports that are typed on paper. A lack of standardization in how crimes are classified can lead to inaccuracies in the data. Another aspect to take into consideration when trying to understand crime data is logistics and planning. For example, a single police station may serve a large neighborhood, deflating the number of reports, or a community with a concentrated amount of shopping centers may experience a higher number of robberies.
</p> 
<p>
Los Angeles, as a city with one of the largest populations of unauthorized immigrants in the U.S. as reported by Pew Research, requires the consideration of illegal immigration as a factor when analyzing crime data. Undocumented immigrants tend to report fewer crimes for fear of being deported. “While there is no direct evidence that the decline is related to concerns within the Hispanic community regarding immigration, the department believes deportation fears may be preventing Hispanic members of the community from reporting when they are victimized,” Los Angeles Police Department said in a statement to Reuters on March 2017.
</p> 
<p>
Though crime data doesn’t provide a perfectly accurate picture of public safety in an area, it does offer a fairly consistent baseline. Crime data allow citizens to make better decisions about where to live, study, work or shop. For example, it can help people know which areas of the city to avoid and at what time they would be more at risk.
</p>
</div>
          <div class="panel-heading" id="">
